Dose-Response Profiling in Heterologous Gene Expression: Insights from Proteome Fraction Analysis - IPTG biosensor

This notebook details the analysis done for obtaining the figures related to the IPTG biosensor (pUCT7-GFP /+ pACYC-Duet) available in the article (Vaccari et al (2023)). A smoothing filter is applied when calculating the growth and production rates. The window size is adjusted according to the data.

An initial visualization of each parameter used in the model (i.e \(OD_{600}\): optical density, \(\text{flu}\): fluorescence, \(\mu\): growth rate, \(\Phi_H\): heterologous fraction, and \(\rho_H\): production rate) is always useful. The lower and upper bounds should include the maximum value of \(\Phi_H\). We suggest the facet wrap view (‘multiple’) of this variable, since it´s relevant for the maximum dose-response profiling method.

view(BL21_lacI_tidy, 'time', 'phi', 'single', 0.5, 10)
Warning: `aes_string()` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.0.0.
Please use tidy evaluation idioms with `aes()`. 
See also `vignette("ggplot2-in-packages")` for more information.

This initial visualization is important as a first approximation to the amount of peaks (maximum) or valleys (minimum) present in the time series. For more than one peak, the maximum method for dose-response profiling might not be useful, and the slope-based method should be applied. For further processing, we select a time interval beginning in \(t = 0.5\) h and ending in \(t = 10\) h.

time_interval <- list(0.5, 10)

Non-linear regression: Maximum method

Since the non-linear regression method used in this work is the nonlinear least squares (nls), an initial guess is needed. Therefore, it´s useful to first visualize the data in a scatter plot. Each point represents the maximum \(\Phi\) value for each concentration of inducer.

drp <- dose_response_profiling(data = BL21_lacI_tidy,
                               time_interval = time_interval,
                               initial_guess = NaN, 
                               flag = FALSE)
Adding missing grouping variables: `Condition`
print(drp[[1]])

Recall the shape of the hill function: \(f_H = H \frac{I_i^n}{I_i^n + k_i^n}\). Then, \(H\) will be the asymptotic value; \(k_i\) controls the concavity of the the curve (i.e the lower the value, the closest the curve is to \(y = x\)); and \(n\) controls the slope of the inflexion point (i.e the higher the value, the steeper the rate of change).

initial_guess <- list(H = 8000, ki = 50, n = 2)
out <- dose_response_profiling(BL21_lacI_tidy, time_interval, initial_guess, TRUE)
Adding missing grouping variables: `Condition`Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
Please use `linewidth` instead.
drp <- out[[1]] # dose-response curve
model <- out[[2]] # model
predictions <- out[[3]] # predictions based on hill coefficients
print(drp)

Non-linear regression: Slope-based method

Applying the smoothing filter with \(n = 5\) windows.

BL21_lacI_tidy <- smooth_filter(BL21_lacI_tidy, 5)

We begin by initializing the linear section matrix, which contains the time intervals from which the slope between the production and growth rates will be calculated. For this particular case, we notice that the Condition column starts at 1 \(\mu M\), even though there is an experiment without the addition of inducer. The removal of this data point corresponds to the method used for estimating the hill coefficients in the single-point method, by which the \(\Phi_H\) value when there is no inducer (i.e leakiness of the genetic circuit) is subtracted from the other values.

linear_section_matrix <- preliminary_slopes(BL21_lacI_tidy, time_interval)
linear_section_matrix

We begin by generating the hook plot for each experimental condition.

hplot <- rates_plot(BL21_lacI_tidy, linear_section_matrix)
print(hplot)

We can manually adjust the minimum and maximum values as needed. For this step, the \(R^2\) value is used as a guiding metric. Recall that inductor[[1]] is not used for the analysis as it´s not part of the previous matrix

inductor <- unique(BL21_lacI_tidy$Condition)
result_plots <- linear_view(BL21_lacI_tidy, inductor[[8]], time_interval, t1 = 2, t2 = 6)

ggarrange(result_plots[[1]], result_plots[[2]], ncol = 2)

In this case, it seems that between the range \(t_1 = 2\) h and \(t_2 = 6\) h, the \(R^2\) value is maximized and considers a great amount of data points. Therefore, we update the linear_section_matrix.

time_range <- c(2, 6)
for (condition in linear_section_matrix$Condition) {

  linear_section_matrix <- manual_adjust(BL21_lacI_tidy, linear_section_matrix, condition, t1 = time_range[[1]], t2 = time_range[[2]])
}

linear_section_matrix

We can visually evaluate the results.

hplot <- rates_plot(BL21_lacI_tidy, linear_section_matrix)
print(hplot)

As a complementary plot, we overlap the hook plots with annotations (red circles: maximum growth rate; black squares: maximum heterologous fraction). Two types of visualizations are available: the overlap of all experimental conditions for an overall comparison, or focusing in a single experimental condition. IMPORTANT: since there is no sense of “time” in this plot, the visualization needs to be complemented.

Following the previous method for the hill function using the single-point method, we generate a new hill function based on the slopes.

After iterating, it seems difficult to directly set the range of linearity. We will then hard-compute the \(t_1\) and \(t_2\) combinations.

# Initial parameters
initial_guess <- list(H = 6000, ki = 50, n = 2)

if (exists("drp_slope")) {
      rm(drp_slope)
    }

# Iterate over values of t1 and t2
for (t1 in seq(0.5, 4, by = 0.1)) {
  for (t2 in seq(10, 5, by = -0.5)) {
    # Apply manual_adjust function
    for (condition in linear_section_matrix$Condition) {
      linear_section_matrix <- manual_adjust(BLR_tidy, linear_section_matrix, condition, t1 = t1, t2 = t2)
    }
    # Apply dose_response_profiling function with try-catch
    tryCatch({
      drp_slope <- dose_response_profiling(linear_section_matrix, time_interval, initial_guess, TRUE)
      # Check if nls algorithm converged
      if (!is.null(drp_slope[[1]])) {
        # Print the combination of t1 and t2
        cat("Converged: t1 =", t1, ", t2 =", t2, "\n")
      }
    }, error = function(e) {
      # If an error occurs, print a message indicating that the combination failed to converge
      #cat("Failed to converge: t1 =", t1, ", t2 =", t2, "\n")
    })
    
    # Remove drp_slope if it exists
    if (exists("drp_slope")) {
      rm(drp_slope)
    }
  }
}
Converged: t1 = 1.8 , t2 = 5 
Converged: t1 = 1.9 , t2 = 5
